and he just says something that you are just like,  

183
00:15:45,960 --> 00:15:51,400
no, because he's got influence. He's a big 
deal at Faire. Most people have this visceral  

184
00:15:51,400 --> 00:15:55,280
reaction of like, oh no, I really don't think 
that's a good idea. Is there something you've  

185
00:15:55,280 --> 00:16:00,840
learned about controlling that bodily reaction of 
like, oh, and then just being positive about it?

186
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:05,720
Yeah, I do think it is just that feedback loop. 
It's not like I don't have the visceral reaction,  

187
00:16:05,720 --> 00:16:11,880
it's just that instead of interpreting it as this 
is a visceral reaction, I got to shut something  

188
00:16:11,880 --> 00:16:18,920
down, it's like, this is a visceral reaction and 
it's a chance to learn more. Just reinterpreting  

189
00:16:18,920 --> 00:16:23,640
some of the feelings in ways that are more 
about opening than about closing stuff down.

190
00:16:23,640 --> 00:16:25,640
Got it, so it's kind of like 
a thinking you do of like,  

191
00:16:25,640 --> 00:16:28,440
okay, hey, let me frame this and 
think about this [inaudible 00:16:28].

192
00:16:28,440 --> 00:16:33,160
For me the most important thing is just taking 
a pause. I think when you just take a pause,  

193
00:16:33,160 --> 00:16:38,840
your body calms down, your mind gets a chance 
to breathe a little bit, and then your response  

194
00:16:38,840 --> 00:16:44,440
is going to be better, but you got to take the 
pause because the immediate visceral reaction,  

195
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:48,360
is not always... It's going to be primal, 
it's going to be protective. It's just  

196
00:16:48,360 --> 00:16:51,760
when you take a pause you're like, 
this is all fine, let's just learn.

197
00:16:52,480 --> 00:16:56,440
I feel like more people are going to 
start using this phrase, fascinating.

198
00:16:56,440 --> 00:16:56,840
Fascinating.

199
00:16:56,840 --> 00:16:57,520
When they hear something [inaudible 00:16:58].

200
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:00,640
It's kind of my tagline. There 
were a few years where I had  

201
00:17:00,640 --> 00:17:03,920
to be careful about not saying it because 
whenever I said it, people would be like,  

202
00:17:03,920 --> 00:17:12,440
she disagrees. So I've had to use a 
thesaurus and expand my words I use.

203
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:16,107
No, that's such a good word. Maybe we'll 
make that the title of this episode.

204
00:17:16,107 --> 00:17:16,115
Totally.

205
00:17:16,115 --> 00:17:20,520
What a great title that would be. So we've 
been talking a bit about the bodily reaction  

206
00:17:20,520 --> 00:17:25,440
to stuff and our lizard brain almost, reacting to 
things. It reminds me of this metaphor that you  

207
00:17:25,440 --> 00:17:31,800
called the dinosaur brain and how it applies 
to product reviews. Talk about what that is.

208
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:35,760
Okay, so a lot of people on my team, they're 
coming in to do product reviews and they're  

209
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:39,360
worried about it. They're stressed out, 
they don't exactly know what to show,  

210
00:17:39,360 --> 00:17:45,560
and the normal temptation is just to show as much 
information as possible because that way you come  

211
00:17:45,560 --> 00:17:50,520
in and you think, hey, the people in this room 
are super smart. I'll show them the information,  

212
00:17:50,520 --> 00:17:53,560
they will come to the right conclusions. 
They'll probably make a better decision  

213
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:59,160
than I'm going to make. So my job is to 
catalog the information and present it. 

214
00:17:59,160 --> 00:18:03,600
And one of the first things that 
I talk to people about is, okay,  

215
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:09,400
for the purposes of this conversation, I'm going 
to put myself in the capitally executive bucket  

216
00:18:09,400 --> 00:18:16,680
because that makes what I'm about to say less 
offensive. Assume that executives have a little  

217
00:18:16,680 --> 00:18:21,800
tiny dinosaur brain. We all have a little 
brontosaurus brain and we can really only  

218
00:18:21,800 --> 00:18:28,960
hold three facts at the same time. We will 
never be able to go deep in the way that  

219
00:18:28,960 --> 00:18:35,720
you are able to do on everything that crosses 
our desk. And so the best service you can do is  

220
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:40,840
actually do the work of making a recommendation. 
That's the way we're going to be complimentary.  

221
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:47,640
The breadth that I normally have to look across 
means that I'm going to be better at things like  

222
00:18:47,640 --> 00:18:51,920
pattern matching or giving you more context or 
telling you stuff that's happening in the company  

223
00:18:51,920 --> 00:18:57,600
or the industry. But what I'm not going to be 
better at is looking at all the information that  

224
00:18:57,600 --> 00:19:03,240
you looked at and coming up with a meaningful 
outcome. That's what you're going to do and  

225
00:19:03,240 --> 00:19:08,080
my little dinosaur brain is going to be like, 
okay, that sounds like a very reasonable pattern,  

226
00:19:08,080 --> 00:19:12,040
I've seen other patterns that look like this. 
Okay, that sounds like an outcome, however,  

227
00:19:12,040 --> 00:19:16,680
it conflicts with this outcome over here. I 
can tell you about that. Does that make sense?

228
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:19,000
Yeah, and I love that you put 
yourself in that bucket. You  

229
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,800
have a dinosaur brain also, it's not other people.

230
00:19:21,800 --> 00:19:27,080
It's a pretty bad, bad look, but it's really true. 
As you get more breadth, you are less and less  

231
00:19:27,080 --> 00:19:32,640
able to go deep on everything that deserves going 
deep and you just end up doing a different service  

232
00:19:32,640 --> 00:19:37,920
than the people on your team, and recognizing 
that as complimentary has been really helpful.

233
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:40,200
You have this phrase, my manager owns context,  

234
00:19:40,200 --> 00:19:42,480
I own the recommendation. 
Kind of along the same lines?

235
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:46,000
Exactly, very similar. And I think the 
thing that was helpful for me there is  

236
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:50,560
that really unlocked what I was looking 
for from my managers because otherwise  

237
00:19:50,560 --> 00:19:55,280
I wanted them to be exactly like me. 
If I assume that I need to bring them  

238
00:19:55,280 --> 00:19:58,640
information and then they would come to 
the same conclusion that I would come to,  

239
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:04,440
that's very narrow. They have to be able to look 
at the exact same information and process it in  

240
00:20:04,440 --> 00:20:09,680
the same way and come out with the same idea. 
Whereas if what they're doing is complimentary  

241
00:20:09,680 --> 00:20:14,920
to me, then I can learn from everyone. They're 
going to just have a different view, they're going  

242
00:20:14,920 --> 00:20:20,600
to have new information that I don't have, and it 
gives me a lot more space to take accountability.

243
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:24,240
Is there any other advice that you could share 
along these lines of just product reviews? So,  

244
00:20:24,240 --> 00:20:29,920
the big takeaway here is just keep 
it simple and have a recommendation.

245
00:20:29,920 --> 00:20:35,800
Keep it simple, have a recommendation. I 
also think that, I think we misuse product  

246
00:20:35,800 --> 00:20:41,520
reviews sometimes as ways to get decisions and 
actually, they should be ways to calibrate on  

247
00:20:41,520 --> 00:20:47,800
principles. So what you don't want is to come 
to a product review for every single that you  

248
00:20:47,800 --> 00:20:52,360
want to make. Instead, what you want is to 
come to a product review with one decision,  

249
00:20:52,360 --> 00:20:55,920
but the goal of that decision is to 
walk out with principles about how to  

250
00:20:55,920 --> 00:20:59,840
make these decisions in the future so that 
you don't have to come to product review,  

251
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:04,080
but you still have this consistent and 
coherent product that you're building. 

252
00:21:04,080 --> 00:21:09,200
And so I think when you flip the frame of 
reviews to being less about, okay, I'm going  

253
00:21:09,200 --> 00:21:14,840
to bring this information to an exec, my manager, 
whoever, and they're going to decide every piece,  

254
00:21:14,840 --> 00:21:19,640
you're not actually building that much more 
capacity in the system. You're getting fast  

255
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:26,120
decision making, but you're not changing who 
can make really good decisions. And I think  

256
00:21:26,120 --> 00:21:30,400
you always want to change the org to constantly 
make better decisions, and a way to do that is  

257
00:21:30,400 --> 00:21:37,600
when you bring these sorts of questions, what you 
talk about is, why did you make this decision?  

258
00:21:37,600 --> 00:21:41,720
What are the trade-offs you have in mind? Who 
are you optimizing for? What timeline are you  

259
00:21:41,720 --> 00:21:46,040
thinking about? What's the risk level we're 
willing to tolerate? And then you don't have  

260
00:21:46,040 --> 00:21:51,360
to come back. You have enough information that 
you can take those principles and run with them.

261
00:21:51,360 --> 00:21:55,480
Is there a framework or a process you use 
for product reviews that might be helpful  

262
00:21:55,480 --> 00:21:59,560
for people to hear? Just like a agenda or 
a way of thinking about just how to set  

263
00:21:59,560 --> 00:22:02,400
up a product review for success? Because 
a lot of people are trying to set these  

264
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:05,200
up at their companies and they're like, I 
don't know if we're doing this optimally.

265
00:22:05,200 --> 00:22:09,960
Yeah, I think everyone's got... I think there's 
so many different takes on frameworks. I don't  

266
00:22:09,960 --> 00:22:14,240
have a single system. I mean, actually I 
think Boz has written about a bunch of this,  

267
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:19,160
and I probably most agree with him. Where there's 
different kinds of product reviews, it's like,  

268
00:22:19,160 --> 00:22:24,680
what are you trying to solve? What's the timeline 
on which you're thinking about for these? Is it  

269
00:22:24,680 --> 00:22:30,560
a philosophy? Is it a strategic shift? Is it a 
day-to-day product decision? And then keeping  

270
00:22:30,560 --> 00:22:36,000
it extremely short and pointed and then making 
sure you walk away with principles, not answers.

271
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:39,400
I think there's a lot of nuance and 
importance there of what you just said,  

272
00:22:39,400 --> 00:22:43,080
which is start with the problem you're solving. 
What are we trying to do here? And the timeline,  

273
00:22:43,080 --> 00:22:45,880
I think that's also really useful 
and important for people to hear.

274
00:22:45,880 --> 00:22:49,960
I think the temptation is always 
to err toward writing more,  

275
00:22:49,960 --> 00:22:54,360
and what I always really recommend people do 
is write whatever you need to write and then  

276
00:22:54,360 --> 00:22:58,600
cut out almost all of it. What you really 
want to bring to any forum, whether it's  

277
00:22:58,600 --> 00:23:06,560
a product review or a written inform or anything 
else, is the minimal amount of information that  

278
00:23:06,560 --> 00:23:13,880
you need to make a clean recommendation because 
then you are forced to be opinionated. Otherwise,  

279
00:23:13,880 --> 00:23:19,080
the opinion can get lost in all of this 
information. You can hide behind, well,  

280
00:23:19,080 --> 00:23:25,240
all of these analyses seem to suggest, and instead 
you should probably just say, looked at all the  

281
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:30,400
data, there's three analyses that suggest this. 
There's one that suggests that, we think that one  

282
00:23:30,400 --> 00:23:36,480
is inaccurate or worth taking the risk on. Let's 
go. Any objections? Let me know. Any new context?  

283
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:43,600
Let me know. That really forces you to deeply 
understand and take an opinion on the material.

284
00:23:43,600 --> 00:23:50,520
Final question, who do you like to invite to these 
product reviews and your thoughts, rules, policy?

285
00:23:50,520 --> 00:23:56,880
Yeah, I mean I do think that usually fewer 
people is better. It leads to a sense of being  

286
00:23:56,880 --> 00:24:03,520
informal and that is really useful because 
it lowers the bar on how complete or strong  

287
00:24:03,520 --> 00:24:08,400
these conversations are and I'd rather have a 
less formal conversation faster than a formal  

288
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:14,240
conversation and lose three weeks in the process 
when we could have been building. I think it needs  

289
00:24:14,240 --> 00:24:18,560
to be cross-functional. I think one of the things 
you want is cross-functional accountability. So  

290
00:24:18,560 --> 00:24:22,200
we want it cross-functional at the leadership 
level and cross-functional at the team presenting  

291
00:24:22,200 --> 00:24:27,400
level. And I think those are normally the groups.
I think the thing that gets hard is you often cut  

292
00:24:27,400 --> 00:24:34,360
out the middle, where if it's a working team 
presenting to the senior leaders on something  

293
00:24:34,360 --> 00:24:39,720
important, it's really hard because it means 
people's managers are not in the room and can't  

294
00:24:39,720 --> 00:24:44,760
help the conversation or other things. And so 
in order to do that, you have to really have  

295
00:24:44,760 --> 00:24:51,440
a bunch of implicit trust inside the team 
that everyone will get the context later,  

296
00:24:51,440 --> 00:24:57,280
that everyone's going to be kind to everyone 
else and you don't need a ton of air cover,  

297
00:24:57,280 --> 00:25:01,960
and that the managers trust their team 
to present in the best possible way.

298
00:25:01,960 --> 00:25:03,960
That is always a stressful 
place for a manager to be,  

299
00:25:03,960 --> 00:25:07,480
where their success is riding in that 
meeting and they're not there and they-

300
00:25:08,280 --> 00:25:12,240
It's so stressful, it's so stressful. I think 
anything you do to make it less stressful is  

301
00:25:12,240 --> 00:25:17,280
useful. But then there've also been times in my 
career where I would keep the room itself small,  

302
00:25:17,280 --> 00:25:20,720
but because we were all trying to 
calibrate on specific principles,  

303
00:25:20,720 --> 00:25:27,440
I would record or broadcast the reading to 
anyone who wanted to see it, just so they  

304
00:25:27,440 --> 00:25:32,040
could all see the principles by which we were 
decision-making and get calibrated on that.

305
00:25:32,040 --> 00:25:36,640
So through your career you've transitioned 
from being the person pitching the products  

306
00:25:36,640 --> 00:25:41,040
and being reviewed to the person 
reviewing and being on the other  

307
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:46,200
side. Is there anything being on this side 
of it that you think is helpful for people  

308
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:53,400
earlier in their career to know about 
that experience, from your angle now?

309
00:25:53,400 --> 00:25:56,080
I mean, I think for what it's worth, I 
think I still do a fair amount of product  

310
00:25:56,080 --> 00:25:59,960
pitching in the past few years because 
there's always someone else to convince.

311
00:25:59,960 --> 00:26:01,240
That's true.

312
00:26:01,240 --> 00:26:04,040
Especially if you want to do something 
dramatically different. Really,  

313
00:26:04,040 --> 00:26:09,920
I think the biggest service for people who are 
starting out a little earlier is that point  

314
00:26:09,920 --> 00:26:17,760
around bringing the recommendation, really 
having the opinion and standing behind it  

315
00:26:17,760 --> 00:26:22,000
with conviction and doing what they need to 
do to build that conviction for themselves.

316
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:25,520
Awesome. You've done this a number of 
times already in this conversation,  

317
00:26:25,520 --> 00:26:28,240
and so I want to spend a little time 
here, which is using metaphors and imagery  

318
00:26:28,920 --> 00:26:34,480
to make your point and get people to understand 
what you're trying to say. So you have this code  

319
00:26:34,480 --> 00:26:39,000
of putting on the coat of the job and this 
dinosaur brain, and so someone told me that  

320
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:43,080
this is just a skill you have where you use 
metaphor and imagery to rally a team, get  

321
00:26:43,080 --> 00:26:47,560
your point across, get people to understand what 
you're trying to say. There's also this metaphor,  

322
00:26:47,560 --> 00:26:52,680
someone told me I need to ask you about the 
hill climb metaphor. Does that ring a bell?

323
00:26:52,680 --> 00:26:53,200
Yeah.

324
00:26:53,200 --> 00:26:55,480
Okay, what is that all about?

325
00:26:55,480 --> 00:26:59,520
For me, the hill climb is all about the 
difference between the local optimum and  

326
00:26:59,520 --> 00:27:05,760
a global optimum. That sounds very abstract, but I 
think a lot of the time when we're doing our job,  

327
00:27:05,760 --> 00:27:09,800
when we're doing life stuff, whatever you're 
doing, you try to just get better and better and  

328
00:27:09,800 --> 00:27:15,000
you optimize your current system and then you feel 
really good about it, and that is great. You're  

329
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:20,640
standing on top of the hill, you're looking down, 
you can see the, I don't know, rolling hills,  

330
00:27:20,640 --> 00:27:27,560
the sheep, the grass, whatever. But then way 
off from the distance you can see a mountain,  

331
00:27:27,560 --> 00:27:34,760
one that's even higher than you can't even 
see the top of it, and you have to decide,  

332
00:27:34,760 --> 00:27:42,240
are you going to take the risk of climbing 
down your hill, crossing an unknown chasm,  

333
00:27:42,240 --> 00:27:47,400
and then climbing back up, just to get to the 
same level you started at with more climbing to  

334
00:27:47,400 --> 00:27:53,080
do to get to that summit? And that is really hard.
I'm thinking of things like, maybe the first time  

335
00:27:53,080 --> 00:27:58,480
I saw this was like a lot of companies were really 
good at desktop and you could see the mobile  

336
00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:06,720
mountain way out over there, but to get there 
you had to really make a lot of trade-offs in  

337
00:28:06,720 --> 00:28:11,480
your core desktop business that you were not 
totally sure were going to pay off when you  

338
00:28:11,480 --> 00:28:15,240
made it to the mobile mountain, and you had 
to do a ton of work. You had to fundamentally  

339
00:28:15,240 --> 00:28:19,560
rewire a lot of what you're doing without a 
guarantee that you're going to get there. I mean,  

340
00:28:19,560 --> 00:28:25,040
you can see it in life when you think about 
new jobs or new moves or new relationships,  

341
00:28:25,560 --> 00:28:30,280
anything that you think about. You are 
giving up something that is working  

342
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:34,800
pretty well without knowing whether you're 
going to make it to the top of that next  

343
00:28:34,800 --> 00:28:42,200
mountain. And that's been really helpful to me 
just to place where I am on different things,  

344
00:28:42,200 --> 00:28:48,360
where you get the inkling that there is a 
much better way to do this, there really is. 

345
00:28:48,360 --> 00:28:53,280
Is it going to be worth going down into the 
valley, climbing up, keeping climbing? Is  

346
00:28:53,280 --> 00:28:58,160
that going to be worth it? Most of the time the 
answer is yes, but it's helpful for me to know,  

347
00:28:58,160 --> 00:29:03,640
boy, this feels like a slog. It is supposed 
to? Because I'm still in the valley and the  

348
00:29:03,640 --> 00:29:08,000
thing that gets me through the valley is 
remembering what the summit feels like.  

349
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:13,160
When you're on top of it and you're like, this 
is great, it was absolutely worth it. My life  

350
00:29:13,160 --> 00:29:18,880
is better in these ways, we're able to solve 
these problems in these ways. It was worth it.

351
00:29:18,880 --> 00:29:24,320
I love that. It feels like a big value 
of the metaphor, which I love is that to  

352
00:29:24,320 --> 00:29:28,760
set expectations, it's going to be really 
hard for a little bit or we will slow down  

353
00:29:28,760 --> 00:29:32,273
what we're trying to do now, but the idea is 
there's a bigger hill and a bigger mountain.

354
00:29:32,273 --> 00:29:34,720
It's a bigger hill and it's worth it.

355
00:29:34,720 --> 00:29:37,120
On this kind of broader idea 
of metaphors and imagery,  

356
00:29:37,120 --> 00:29:39,200
is there something there that 
you've learned of just like,  

357
00:29:39,200 --> 00:29:42,400
this works really well, I'm going to invest in 
becoming better at this, or is this something  

358
00:29:42,400 --> 00:29:46,640
that's come natural to you? Anything you 
can share about that skill and approach?

359
00:29:46,640 --> 00:29:52,320
I think this one came from, I worked for a 
manager, his name was Eric Antino, and he was  

360
00:29:52,320 --> 00:29:58,200
just a master of the metaphor and analogies. 
And so whenever I would bring him something,  

361
00:29:58,200 --> 00:30:02,600
he would be like, how is this 
product going to make you feel,  

362
00:30:02,600 --> 00:30:06,680
and when is the last time that you 
felt this way? And you can say, oh,  

363
00:30:06,680 --> 00:30:10,120
I felt this way when I was hanging with my 
friends in Dolores Park and he'd be like,  

364
00:30:10,120 --> 00:30:18,080
cool, tell me what it feels like, why that's the 
analogy, what ramifications come out of that? 

365
00:30:18,080 --> 00:30:24,160
And one thing I like to do is try to build 
an emulator for different people in my head,  

366
00:30:24,160 --> 00:30:30,560
because I've just had the good fortune of working 
with an amazing number of very different leaders,  

367
00:30:30,560 --> 00:30:34,040
and so he's one of the people I tried to 
build an emulator for where I'd be like, okay,  

368
00:30:34,040 --> 00:30:40,440
I see this thing. I don't know how to solve this 
problem. How would Eric describe this? I've tried  

369
00:30:40,440 --> 00:30:44,960
to build one for Boz, which is all about principle 
