00:46:10,080 --> 00:46:16,320
this is the dot on the map. And I was always 
like, how could anything could happen? Who  

557
00:46:16,320 --> 00:46:21,600
would I be to say I know how the world's going 
to develop and here's where we're heading? 

558
00:46:21,600 --> 00:46:28,400
And so for me, a lot of it was actually learning 
the things that made me feel confident in my own  

559
00:46:28,400 --> 00:46:32,400
opinion. And there's a bunch of things that 
do make me feel confident in my opinion. When  

560
00:46:32,400 --> 00:46:36,600
I talk to specific customers and I feel 
like I can build an emulator for them,  

561
00:46:36,600 --> 00:46:41,760
like a customer on my shoulder where I can say, 
oh, I talked to this person working in this job,  

562
00:46:41,760 --> 00:46:46,640
here's what they would say if I showed them this 
product or this strategy. So, I think talking to  

563
00:46:46,640 --> 00:46:52,160
customers is a big unlock for me and feeling like 
I have unique knowledge of the customer. I think  

564
00:46:52,160 --> 00:46:59,240
working through different product iterations 
of, if we thought this was the right outcome,  

565
00:46:59,240 --> 00:47:03,680
what would it really look like from a product 
perspective or a product portfolio in three  

566
00:47:03,680 --> 00:47:10,520
to five years? And which of those seems right 
or rational or it will go the way I think the  

567
00:47:10,520 --> 00:47:16,800
world goes. I think asking for other opinions. 
Sometimes I run surveys to the leadership team  

568
00:47:16,800 --> 00:47:22,320
where I'm just like, what percentage of our 
revenue is going to come from small businesses  

569
00:47:22,320 --> 00:47:27,440
versus big businesses in three years? And if we 
all agree on that topic, we should just take it  

570
00:47:27,440 --> 00:47:31,480
as the truth and we should just fill it. If we 
disagree, then we should talk about it and we  

571
00:47:31,480 --> 00:47:35,800
should talk about the strategic ramifications 
if we chose one path or the other path. 

572
00:47:35,800 --> 00:47:41,680
So for me, it was getting more comfortable 
having an opinion, honestly, about how  

573
00:47:41,680 --> 00:47:46,520
the world was going to go, and also feeling 
comfortable that we would be able to change  

574
00:47:46,520 --> 00:47:52,480
it when we learned that maybe that wasn't exactly 
right. We would have the machine, the execution  

575
00:47:52,480 --> 00:48:00,520
machine behind it to try it out and then change 
and iterate and improve with customer feedback.

576
00:48:00,520 --> 00:48:04,080
At which point in your career 
was this overcoming this fear  

577
00:48:04,080 --> 00:48:07,720
and uncertainty? Was it sometime within Facebook?

578
00:48:07,720 --> 00:48:13,280
It was sometime within Facebook. It was really 
when I was stepping into the bigger ads jobs,  

579
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:20,000
getting to be Head of Product for Facebook ads. 
I got feedback, I got a lot of feedback over  

580
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:28,600
the course of my career and some of the 
stacking of feedback was basically like,  

581
00:48:28,600 --> 00:48:32,640
you could be the smartest person in the room, 
but it doesn't matter if people don't like you,  

582
00:48:33,600 --> 00:48:42,520
which is very complicated feedback and I wouldn't 
give that feedback to anyone else, but I took it  

583
00:48:42,520 --> 00:48:45,960
very seriously. It was coming from so many 
different places, it was coming from people  

584
00:48:45,960 --> 00:48:54,920
I'm really trusted. And so I went out of my way 
to be more likable, which for me ended up being  

585
00:48:57,880 --> 00:49:03,560
shrinking myself a little bit and not 
being so aggressive and not being so  

586
00:49:03,560 --> 00:49:10,120
opinionated, being more unobjectionable.
And the weird part is that it worked for a  

587
00:49:10,120 --> 00:49:15,200
long time. People were more likely to work with 
me, they were more likely to say nice things. I  

588
00:49:15,200 --> 00:49:20,120
mean, I take this to extremes. I wore earth 
tones for two years because I was just like,  

589
00:49:20,120 --> 00:49:26,840
I got to fade back a little bit. And then at 
some point I actually had to do a leadership  

590
00:49:26,840 --> 00:49:31,800
job and my team was like, well, what do you 
think? What's your opinion? And I was like,  

591
00:49:31,800 --> 00:49:35,840
you've been telling me not to have an 
opinion for so long. And so it took a  

592
00:49:35,840 --> 00:49:41,480
little bit of work to get back to, 
oh yeah, I have a lot of opinions,  

593
00:49:41,480 --> 00:49:46,240
I have a lot of thoughts. It is okay for me 
to express. It is needed, my team needs me  

594
00:49:46,240 --> 00:49:52,720
to have these opinions and thoughts and be a 
leader who can take ownership and be visible.

595
00:49:52,720 --> 00:49:56,640
Thanks for sharing that. Do you 
think that was the right approach,  

596
00:49:57,640 --> 00:50:02,360
going and indexing far to the other end and 
then realizing that maybe that's too far,  

597
00:50:02,360 --> 00:50:05,400
or do you think you would've done 
things differently looking back?

598
00:50:05,400 --> 00:50:12,520
Yeah, it's one of my Roman empires. I think 
about this every so often, way too much,  

599
00:50:12,520 --> 00:50:17,560
I think. Especially because I talked to other 
senior women who received similar feedback and  

600
00:50:17,560 --> 00:50:24,960
chose not to act on it or did act on it, and what 
happened to their paths were different. I think  

601
00:50:24,960 --> 00:50:30,840
where I landed is I wouldn't give that feedback to 
someone else. And the way I do give that feedback,  

602
00:50:30,840 --> 00:50:36,480
actually, because I think there is a lot of 
really useful information in that. The way I  

603
00:50:36,480 --> 00:50:41,840
do give that feedback is, you do need to be able 
to work with a broader range of people and the  

604
00:50:41,840 --> 00:50:47,000
way to do that is to expand your tool sets. 
You're not going to make yourself smaller,  

605
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:52,440
you're not going to be any less of who you 
are, but you are going to build new tools,  

606
00:50:53,440 --> 00:50:58,280
new keys to unlock new different kinds 
of doors. And that is only going to  

607
00:50:58,280 --> 00:51:03,640
make you bigger and more powerful and more 
expansive. But the end outcome is the same,  

608
00:51:03,640 --> 00:51:08,560
is that you can work with more different styles 
