609
00:51:08,560 --> 00:51:12,840
I love that framing. There's an episode that's 
going to come out before this episode with  

610
00:51:12,840 --> 00:51:17,920
this professor from Stanford, Jeffrey Pfeffer, 
who teaches a class called The Path to Power,  

611
00:51:17,920 --> 00:51:22,640
which is how to become powerful in the 
world. And he actually has a big lesson  

612
00:51:22,640 --> 00:51:28,920
that many people hate hearing, which is, you 
don't need to be authentic in the workplace,  

613
00:51:29,480 --> 00:51:33,160
what you're trying to achieve, you're trying to 
achieve stuff and you can do... You need to use  

614
00:51:33,160 --> 00:51:38,280
tools that you need to use to achieve the thing 
you want to achieve. So sometimes don't be exactly  

615
00:51:38,280 --> 00:51:42,200
who you are and act in a slightly different 
way, which is basically what you're describing.

616
00:51:42,200 --> 00:51:44,960
More tools. I think that's 
a theme that's coming up,  

617
00:51:44,960 --> 00:51:50,120
is just like, I'm all about more lenses, 
more keys, more tools in general because  

618
00:51:50,120 --> 00:51:54,360
why not? Why not have access to 
more different styles of things?

619
00:51:54,360 --> 00:51:56,520
Something that you were talking about  

620
00:51:57,600 --> 00:52:03,120
subtly is the being a woman in tech and being a 
female leader. I imagine you've gone through some  

621
00:52:03,120 --> 00:52:07,960
stuff that isn't what something men would've gone 
through. Is there anything there that you want to  

622
00:52:07,960 --> 00:52:13,400
share or anything you've learned about just 
being really successful as a woman in tech?

623
00:52:13,400 --> 00:52:18,640
I think we've talked through some of them. I think 
one, you get a different style of feedback and a  

624
00:52:18,640 --> 00:52:24,160
lot of the ways to interpret that feedback. I 
think to this day, I get feedback that is about  

625
00:52:24,160 --> 00:52:31,160
walking a very narrow tightrope where not only 
do you have to change a bunch of things and do  

626
00:52:31,160 --> 00:52:36,120
a bunch of things that are important, you have 
to make people feel a certain way about how you  

627
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:41,040
do them and the ways that they want you to make 
you feel are diametrically opposite. Some people  

628
00:52:41,040 --> 00:52:44,800
are going to be like, be more directive so that 
way everyone knows your thing. Some people are  

629
00:52:44,800 --> 00:52:50,400
going to say be less directive so people can 
come to their own conclusions. Some people are  

630
00:52:50,400 --> 00:52:53,480
going to say move faster because there's 
always more you can do. Some people are  

631
00:52:53,480 --> 00:52:57,200
going to say move less fast because otherwise 
you're going to end up steamrolling people. 

632
00:52:57,200 --> 00:53:01,400
And a lot of it is personal, there's a bunch 
research about how women get a lot more personal  

633
00:53:01,400 --> 00:53:06,800
feedback that is less about the content of their 
role and more about their style, I think that is  

634
00:53:06,800 --> 00:53:13,680
still true and there's often a kernel of truth in 
it. For me, this is forever work. I do have biases  

635
00:53:13,680 --> 00:53:20,000
toward execution and being directive and things 
like that, but I think learning how to interpret  

636
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:26,440
and respond to feedback has been a really 
important point for me and making my choices of,  

637
00:53:27,360 --> 00:53:34,480
just because I'm getting feedback doesn't mean I 
immediately need to respond to all of it. There's  

638
00:53:34,480 --> 00:53:43,520
a step in between where I can choose, is this 
feedback I want to take action on in this exact  

639
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:47,560
way? Am I going to look for more themes, take 
action in a different way, or am I going to  

640
00:53:47,560 --> 00:53:51,400
say this is who I am and I understand the 
trade-offs, I'm going to do a better job  

641
00:53:51,400 --> 00:53:57,280
of giving people context on the decisions I'm 
making and why I'm choosing these trade-offs.  

642
00:53:57,280 --> 00:54:01,720
But actually this is part of how I want to 
