664
00:55:56,880 --> 00:56:00,920
I love that. I want to move to a different 
topic. There's a few things I definitely  

665
00:56:00,920 --> 00:56:04,360
wanted to touch on while we had our 
time together. One is that I hear,  

666
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:07,440
now this is going to be a total tangent, but I 
think it's really important and I'm excited to  

667
00:56:07,440 --> 00:56:12,000
talk about it. I hear you're really good at 
setting goals and aligning incentives really  

668
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:16,480
well for teams. One of your colleagues told 
me you're best in class at building product  

669
00:56:16,480 --> 00:56:22,160
orgs and figuring out how product orgs can best 
work with other teams. I'm curious if there's  

670
00:56:22,160 --> 00:56:26,240
any tricks or lessons you can share here about 
what you've learned about how to do this well.

671
00:56:27,760 --> 00:56:34,760
Yeah, I mean I think one thing is to try to 
decouple all the things we're trying to do.  

672
00:56:34,760 --> 00:56:39,800
Sometimes when you give people direction, you're 
like, okay, everybody just go get revenue or  

673
00:56:39,800 --> 00:56:44,200
everybody just go get GMV. And it seems obvious 
because that's the thing you have to do as a  

674
00:56:44,200 --> 00:56:51,880
company, but there's only a few places where you 
are guaranteed to get that and it's measurable  

675
00:56:51,880 --> 00:56:59,320
and you can do it. And that leads to what I call 
toddler soccer, where everybody just runs to the  

676
00:56:59,320 --> 00:57:06,040
same surface or the same customer set or the 
same exact product where you can do this and  

677
00:57:06,040 --> 00:57:09,640
it's measurable and you end up, everyone's 
tripping on each other, everyone's trying,  

678
00:57:09,640 --> 00:57:14,440
nobody really gets contact on the ball, there's 
no coordination. I have three kids, I've  

679
00:57:14,440 --> 00:57:20,560
watched a lot of toddlers play soccer. [inaudible 
00:57:18], it's a very fresh, very fresh metaphor. 

680
00:57:20,560 --> 00:57:26,440
And instead, one of the things I like to 
do is just detangle, okay, as a company,  

681
00:57:26,440 --> 00:57:30,320
let's think about our customers. Let's think 
about all the things they're going to need  

682
00:57:30,320 --> 00:57:35,840
in their journey. Let's think about how we 
will know how we will match our own metrics  

683
00:57:35,840 --> 00:57:41,000
to customer success. Let's play the entire 
field. What would it look like if we could  

684
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:47,800
detangle it so that every team we had internally 
had a different goal that ladders into a goal  

685
00:57:47,800 --> 00:57:54,440
framework that's actually the thing that we need 
to do to solve the full customer impact? And then  

686
00:57:54,440 --> 00:57:59,920
you don't have the same swim lanes problem. You 
have plenty of room for people to make progress  

687
00:57:59,920 --> 00:58:05,040
on their lanes. They all know how they fit into 
the bigger picture, and it just opens up a lot  

688
00:58:05,040 --> 00:58:11,000
more growth for every team and it makes sure that 
we're solving the customer problem end to end.

689
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:14,320
Is there an example that you could share 
to make this even more concrete from say,  

690
00:58:14,320 --> 00:58:19,080
WhatsApp or Facebook or Instagram or anything like 
that, where you can share some of these goals that  

691
00:58:19,080 --> 00:58:24,320
you've like, oh, this worked out really well? I 
know it's probably private information and partly-

692
00:58:25,240 --> 00:58:31,160
It might be trickier. I mean, maybe going 
back to the GMV example. Maybe instead of  

693
00:58:31,160 --> 00:58:36,920
motivating everyone on GMV, you motivate them on 
GMV per surface and you divide up the surfaces,  

694
00:58:36,920 --> 00:58:43,800
or maybe you motivate them on actually different 
goals that underlie. When you think about GMV,  

695
00:58:43,800 --> 00:58:48,920
what are all the various engagements, customer 
engagements that lead to GMV? Can you goal on  

696
00:58:48,920 --> 00:58:53,400
those input metrics, can you goal on number of 
people who visit, number of people who convert,  

697
00:58:53,400 --> 00:58:59,480
number of people who reorder, number, etc? 
Rather than going strictly on the output.

698
00:58:59,480 --> 00:59:03,560
So the core advice here is each team 
should have different goals that are  

699
00:59:03,560 --> 00:59:07,760
part of this metrics tree that ladder 
up to revenue, GMV, something like that?

700
00:59:07,760 --> 00:59:11,360
Whatever, yeah. The thing that 
best matches the overall customer  

701
00:59:11,360 --> 00:59:14,480
outcome that mirrors the company outcome as well.

702
00:59:14,480 --> 00:59:16,960
Got it. And there's always this 
balance between it's actually  

703
00:59:16,960 --> 00:59:20,680
the best metric versus it's something 
they can move and understand and it's  

704
00:59:20,680 --> 00:59:24,400
easy to watch and it's movable 
and things like that, right?

705
00:59:24,400 --> 00:59:28,480
Yeah, and you have to have faith that 
it is actually connected to that output  

706
00:59:28,480 --> 00:59:33,280
metric. You don't want to create a metric that's 
disconnected just to make a team feel good. It  

707
00:59:33,280 --> 00:59:37,840
really does need to solve the customer problem 
and that's reflected in company's performance,  

708
00:59:37,840 --> 00:59:41,840
but you can usually break it down into 
smaller pieces and I think that breaking  

709
00:59:41,840 --> 00:59:46,240
down into smaller pieces and assigning 
those out to teams, that's really helpful.

710
00:59:46,240 --> 00:59:48,040
Is there anything else along these lines of things  

711
00:59:48,040 --> 00:59:53,560
you've learned about helping teams work 
together and not play toddler soccer,  

712
00:59:53,560 --> 00:59:58,880
beyond having different goals that all 
ladder up to the one that really matters?

713
00:59:58,880 --> 01:00:05,480
I think there's value in also acknowledging that 
teams are going to have different incentives. Even  

714
01:00:05,480 --> 01:00:10,680
inside a team like cross-functional 
teams on the same pod or whatever,  

715
01:00:10,680 --> 01:00:13,840
are going to have different incentives, they're 
going to come in with different information,  

716
01:00:13,840 --> 01:00:18,840
they're going to have disagreements. And 
certainly, different teams inside a company  

717
01:00:18,840 --> 01:00:21,720
or different pillars inside a company, 
different products inside, they're all  

718
01:00:21,720 --> 01:00:26,800
going to have different incentives, and I think 
sometimes that feels like something is going  

719
01:00:26,800 --> 01:00:33,960
wrong when people disagree, but actually, that's 
just a sign of healthy tension and knowledge. 

720
01:00:33,960 --> 01:00:39,600
I think the thing that makes tension healthy 
is one, when you can acknowledge it and say,  

721
01:00:39,600 --> 01:00:42,840
yeah, of course there's tension. You're bringing 
different information than I'm bringing. We should  

722
01:00:42,840 --> 01:00:50,640
be disagreeing. No one's a bad person, no one 
is coming in with poor intent. Everyone's doing  

723
01:00:50,640 --> 01:00:54,600
the thing they are supposed to do and that 
is a useful thing to do. And then you have  

724
01:00:54,600 --> 01:00:59,480
to agree on an outcome that you're aiming for. 
If you disagree on what the company outcome is  

725
01:00:59,480 --> 01:01:03,320
or what the customer outcome is, then you've 
got some structural stuff you need to work out  

726
01:01:03,320 --> 01:01:08,360
and normally you just have to escalate it, but if 
you agree on like, we're all trying to move this  

727
01:01:08,360 --> 01:01:13,680
metric by changing this customer experience, then 
all you're doing is having a conversation about  

728
01:01:13,680 --> 01:01:19,000
the best way to do that using the different 
information that everyone is bringing. And I  

729
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:24,720
think that's super important to just have 
as a rational, open, explicit discussion,  

730
01:01:24,720 --> 01:01:31,400
as opposed to trying to hide it or pocket vetoing 
or something else. Because you assume that when  

731
01:01:31,400 --> 01:01:37,160
someone disagrees with you that, I don't know, 
there's something emotional or wrong about it.

732
01:01:37,160 --> 01:01:40,120
But it's fascinating.

733
01:01:40,120 --> 01:01:41,200
Exactly.

734
01:01:41,200 --> 01:01:44,480
There's a piece of advice I once heard 
from the Head of Product at Airbnb once  

735
01:01:44,480 --> 01:01:48,000
where we were trying to find, reorg 
the business and try to figure out the  

736
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:52,240
best org and his advice and something he 
realized is, there's never the best org,  

737
01:01:52,240 --> 01:01:55,920
there's just the best idea we have at 
the time with the here's the things  

738
01:01:55,920 --> 01:01:59,560
we know are not going to be optimal about 
it and let's build processes around that.

739
01:01:59,560 --> 01:02:05,920
I think that's my take on leadership in 
general. Especially as you get more senior,  

740
01:02:05,920 --> 01:02:11,160
you can only make bad decisions. At some 
point someone can bring you a problem,  

741
01:02:11,160 --> 01:02:16,480
you can recognize a problem and you can solve 
it, and there's so much happiness in solving  

742
01:02:16,480 --> 01:02:21,680
that and tying a bow around it. But as you 
get senior, the only problems you'll see are  

743
01:02:21,680 --> 01:02:25,840
ones that are fundamentally unsolvable because 
otherwise, someone would've solved it before  

744
01:02:26,360 --> 01:02:32,960
they got to you. And so all you're doing is 
choosing which branch of suboptimal you're  

745
01:02:32,960 --> 01:02:38,240
going to put your name on and describing the 
principles you're using and the context and  

746
01:02:38,240 --> 01:02:43,560
the fact that it's suboptimal, but it's still the 
best thing. I think that's a really hard thing,  

747
01:02:43,560 --> 01:02:50,160
is just to recognize and acknowledge that 
increasingly people only see you do, make  

748
01:02:50,160 --> 01:02:56,040
suboptimal decisions and from a distance they're 
just like, why is that person only making bad  

749
01:02:56,040 --> 01:03:01,720
decisions? And it's because those are your only 
options. All you can do is choose the least bad,  

750
01:03:01,720 --> 01:03:06,600
the best possible for the time, 
for the problem that's consistent  

751
01:03:06,600 --> 01:03:10,800
that makes sense with the framework, and 
that's been a tough thing to learn too.

752
01:03:10,800 --> 01:03:12,720
You said somewhere that as you get more senior,  

753
01:03:12,720 --> 01:03:14,960
you get worse at everything 
because the problems get harder.

754
01:03:14,960 --> 01:03:20,520
Yes, exactly. I mean, it's a kind of 
dark view of leadership where yeah,  

755
01:03:20,520 --> 01:03:25,400
you can't fully solve problems, you have to say 
no a lot people are unhappy with you. I thought  

756
01:03:25,400 --> 01:03:30,200
as you get more senior, everyone listens to 
you and they like you and you could just say  

757
01:03:30,200 --> 01:03:36,920
a thing and then it happens and that is not 
at all accurate. It really is, most of the  

758
01:03:36,920 --> 01:03:45,200
decisions you make are not going to be perfect.
And I think I'm all about just normalizing and  

759
01:03:45,200 --> 01:03:51,120
acknowledging those hard truths because otherwise, 
I feel like I'm failing. And if I just know that  

760
01:03:51,120 --> 01:03:56,040
something is normal that it's part of the 
job, then it's not me. It's just like, okay,  

761
01:03:56,040 --> 01:04:00,760
this is a fact of the job that I have to get 
accustomed to if I want to have this kind of  

762
01:04:00,760 --> 01:04:06,680
impact. And there's something about having 
the impact, being able to serve the customer,  

763
01:04:06,680 --> 01:04:10,800
being able to be part of this team, there's 
something about it that is so worthwhile that  

764
01:04:10,800 --> 01:04:16,400
it's worth being terrible at everything 
and being visibly terrible at everything  

765
01:04:16,400 --> 01:04:21,560
because that is the best way that I have 
to have that kind of impact in the world.

766
01:04:21,560 --> 01:04:28,320
I think this is really important for early ICPMs 
to hear because they see their CPO and founders  

767
01:04:28,320 --> 01:04:31,840
making all these decisions and they're like, 
what the hell? That's a terrible idea, why are  

768
01:04:31,840 --> 01:04:38,335
they doing this? What you're saying is just like 
it's the best... Options are limited and then-

769
01:04:38,335 --> 01:04:38,356
[inaudible 01:04:38].

770
01:04:38,356 --> 01:04:39,840
... nothing's going to be optimal.

771
01:04:39,840 --> 01:04:43,440
Yeah, no org is optimal. It's definitely 
not. You can optimize for the people you  

772
01:04:43,440 --> 01:04:46,320
have and you can optimize for the products 
you have, can optimize for the customers you  

773
01:04:46,320 --> 01:04:51,120
have and you can optimize for the technology 
you have. Those are the options that you have,  

774
01:04:51,120 --> 01:04:57,400
and in every one of those you trade off 
everything else. And so you just have to know,  

775
01:04:57,400 --> 01:05:02,040
there's not going to be a perfect where all of it 
works and that's okay. That is part of the fun of  

776
01:05:02,040 --> 01:05:07,120
it. That's part of getting to do this work, is 
continuing to improve, but it's hard. It's hard  

777
01:05:07,120 --> 01:05:12,800
when people, it's hard, especially when you want 
everyone to think you're so great at everything.

778
01:05:12,800 --> 01:05:16,640
This idea you mentioned of as a senior person 
solving people's problems, feeling really good,  

779
01:05:16,640 --> 01:05:20,960
reminds me. Rolling to this, there's this 
Harvard Business Review article from the '70s  

780
01:05:20,960 --> 01:05:24,600
or '80s or something about monkeys on your 
back. Have you read this or heard of this?

781
01:05:24,600 --> 01:05:25,640
Oh yeah, yeah, I did.

782
01:05:26,240 --> 01:05:28,393
Where it's basically like as a 
manager, [inaudible 01:05:28]-

783
01:05:28,393 --> 01:05:31,520
You're trying to get monkey off 
of your back on people's backs?

784
01:05:31,520 --> 01:05:31,960
Exactly.

785
01:05:31,960 --> 01:05:32,080
Right, right, right.

786
01:05:32,080 --> 01:05:35,560
People come to you, Ami, here's my 
monkey, please take it for me and  

787
01:05:35,560 --> 01:05:38,800
feed it for me and take care of it. 
And your job as a leader is to keep  

788
01:05:38,800 --> 01:05:45,912
the monkeys on people's backs and help them 
figure out how to feed this monkey themself.

789
01:05:45,912 --> 01:05:45,929
It's a weird one.

790
01:05:45,929 --> 01:05:49,240
To get it off their back. It's very visceral. 
I want to talk about Faire and your current  

791
01:05:49,240 --> 01:05:54,600
role as a final section of our chat. First 
of all, what was it like starting something  

792
01:05:54,600 --> 01:06:00,520
completely new after 15 years at Meta 
at the various properties of Meta?

793
01:06:00,520 --> 01:06:06,880
Yeah, I mean, I was so lucky. I had such an 
amazing run at Meta. I got to work with amazing  

794
01:06:06,880 --> 01:06:13,600
leaders, truly great products. And I came to 
Faire for the same reason that I've been anywhere,  

795
01:06:13,600 --> 01:06:17,720
because I believe in the people and I believe 
in the mission. A lot of my family in India is  

796
01:06:17,720 --> 01:06:23,960
in wholesale and local retail, which is what Faire 
does, and so it was also a very personal thing for  

797
01:06:23,960 --> 01:06:27,680
me too. I felt like I knew those customers. I'm a 
huge fan of small businesses, I got to work with  

798
01:06:27,680 --> 01:06:34,120
a bunch of them in previous jobs as well.
I would say coming to Faire, I mean,  

799
01:06:34,120 --> 01:06:38,560
one of the things I always think about is 
that especially as you are more senior,  

800
01:06:38,560 --> 01:06:45,760
ramping on anywhere feels terrible because you 
expect to be as good at your new job as you  

801
01:06:45,760 --> 01:06:51,560
were when you left your last job, but you forget 
that at your last job, you were there for years,  

802
01:06:51,560 --> 01:06:57,480
you had years to build up the vocabulary and the 
cultural context and the network and the product  

803
01:06:57,480 --> 01:07:02,880
knowledge, and then you're stepping in somewhere 
where you know none of that, but you have the same  

804
01:07:02,880 --> 01:07:08,360
expectations of yourself of being able to have an 
impact and improve things and help your team. And  

805
01:07:08,360 --> 01:07:15,000
so I always just try to remind myself, it's going 
to take time and what's most important is not for  

806
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:20,000
me to try to come in and change everything 
immediately, but to learn enough to be able  

807
01:07:20,000 --> 01:07:29,320
to change things like 60 or 90 or 120 days in the 
future. And so that breathing helps a little bit. 

808
01:07:29,320 --> 01:07:34,160
It was also really interesting because Faire was 
entirely new to me. It was a new business model,  

809
01:07:34,160 --> 01:07:39,080
it was a whole new set of people. It was a 
whole new set of customer problems. And so  

810
01:07:39,080 --> 01:07:43,920
every interaction I just had to learn so much. 
I had to learn, who is this person? How do they  

811
01:07:43,920 --> 01:07:47,400
see the world? What's the problem they're 
talking to me about? What's the customer  

812
01:07:47,400 --> 01:07:54,480
impact, I think? So it was just a dramatic 
learning curve, which I always really love. 

813
01:07:54,480 --> 01:08:01,000
Maybe the last thing I'd say is, again, I was 
super lucky at Meta. I think I always had this  

814
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:07,400
maybe deep-seated insecurity that maybe I was 
only good at Meta. Maybe there was something  

815
01:08:07,400 --> 01:08:13,720
about that network of people and how great 
they were and how well I knew those products,  

816
01:08:13,720 --> 01:08:19,080
and maybe I wouldn't be that successful somewhere 
without that scaffolding. And so leaving and being  

817
01:08:19,080 --> 01:08:27,120
able to go somewhere else and lead through 
change and a new place, a new customer set,  

818
01:08:27,120 --> 01:08:34,000
a new business model, that's also been 
really, really affirming for me, honestly.

819
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:36,219
Well, you have a lot of fans at 
Faire from the people I know there.

820
01:08:36,219 --> 01:08:36,240
[inaudible 01:08:36].

821
01:08:36,240 --> 01:08:41,920
And so clearly, things are going well, at least 
as far as I can tell. Something that I think is,  

822
01:08:41,920 --> 01:08:49,680
Faire definitely has, and a lot of companies have, 
is a very product minded visionary founder. And  

823
01:08:49,680 --> 01:08:54,880
CPOs classically last a year or two, and then 
they're like, ah, this sucks. The founder just  

824
01:08:54,880 --> 01:08:59,320
tells me what to do and what's the point of this 
role? And it's so frustrating. I'm curious just  

825
01:08:59,320 --> 01:09:05,160
what you've learned about, at least so far, about 
working with someone like that as a CPO and not  

826
01:09:05,160 --> 01:09:09,880
just being this middle person between what the 
founder wants to do with the team, this building.

827
01:09:09,880 --> 01:09:16,080
Yeah, I mean, this is going to sound so naive, 
but I literally didn't know how important it was  

828
01:09:16,080 --> 01:09:21,880
for me to have such a great relationship with 
the CEO, because I always had great relation,  

829
01:09:21,880 --> 01:09:25,480
I was lucky, I had great relationships with 
a lot of people at my previous jobs. I was  

830
01:09:25,480 --> 01:09:28,280
like, oh, of course it's going to be fine, 
everyone's going to let me do what I want,  

831
01:09:28,280 --> 01:09:35,920
whatever. And I think I just got really lucky 
because Max is an amazing CEO, who's also super  

832
01:09:35,920 --> 01:09:42,360
growth mindset and super open to talking over 
ideas, even when they involve a lot of change. 

833
01:09:42,360 --> 01:09:47,560
So when I was onboarding, one of the 
things I always like to do is write a list  

834
01:09:47,560 --> 01:09:51,360
of observations. I go out and talk to, I have 
one-on-ones with a lot of people, and I write,  

835
01:09:51,360 --> 01:09:55,520
here's the themes that I'm hearing. Here's what's 
going well, here's what's not going well. And  

836
01:09:55,520 --> 01:10:01,040
that's a way for me to both share what I'm seeing 
and build some credibility and trust that way,  

837
01:10:01,040 --> 01:10:03,880
but also for people to give me feedback and 
be like, oh, you're wrong about this, just  

838
01:10:03,880 --> 01:10:14,160
so I can correct my starting point of knowledge.
And with Max, I also wrote a parallel document of  

839
01:10:14,160 --> 01:10:20,720
hot takes. So once a quarter or so for the first 
year, I'd write a document that was just like,  

840
01:10:20,720 --> 01:10:25,680
hey, for sake of provocation, if we wanted 
to fundamentally change a few things, here's  

841
01:10:25,680 --> 01:10:33,000
ideas on what we could fundamentally change. And 
Max, very, very well could have just been like,  

842
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:38,880
hey, can you please just run product? That's 
you're job, can you please do that? And instead,  

843
01:10:38,880 --> 01:10:45,840
he and the entire rest of the executive team were 
like, yeah, let's step through these. Let's talk  

844
01:10:45,840 --> 01:10:51,120
about which of these we should try, let's talk 
about maybe context you don't have for why these  

845
01:10:51,120 --> 01:10:58,960
don't make sense or why we don't do these. 
And that was such a gift because I was able  

846
01:10:58,960 --> 01:11:05,600
to build such a great relationship, a trusting and 
complimentary relationship with Max and the rest  

847
01:11:05,600 --> 01:11:12,360
of the exec team, and also that he took seriously 
things that he really didn't have to that I have  

848
01:11:12,360 --> 01:11:18,520
so much respect for that, and I think I got really 
lucky in just finding a great CEO and exec team.

849
01:11:18,520 --> 01:11:21,800
Is there anything you learned about 
this vetting process? Say you're a  

850
01:11:21,800 --> 01:11:25,360
founder looking for a head of product, A CPO,  

851
01:11:25,360 --> 01:11:31,920
any advice for how they might vet this person 
to make sure they are good fit and will last?

852
01:11:31,920 --> 01:11:36,120
What I'd say to everyone else is, make sure 
you just have a mind meld with a CEO. Before  

853
01:11:36,120 --> 01:11:42,240
you decide to take the job, spend a day together, 
understand how they think and how they operate,  

854
01:11:42,240 --> 01:11:48,000
and whether you're going to work together in 
a way that feels really high fidelity and high  

855
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:53,920
trust and you're going to have room. I mean, I'm 
not a founder by any stretch and so when founders  

856
01:11:53,920 --> 01:11:58,960
ask me what should I look for in a head of product 
or CPO, I say something a little bit different,  

857
01:11:58,960 --> 01:12:06,880
which is, make sure that you really need the level 
of seniority that you are hiring. I think that a  

858
01:12:06,880 --> 01:12:14,040
lot of founders think, I need a CPO, I need a VP 
of product, I need someone who's really senior,  

859
01:12:14,040 --> 01:12:18,920
when often the founder has a bunch of the 
vision and knowledge, and what they really  

860
01:12:18,920 --> 01:12:23,000
need is somebody to build the product. They 
don't need somebody who's going to scale the  

861
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:29,280
team or build systems like they've got enough 
of that. And so that to me is part of building  

862
01:12:29,280 --> 01:12:36,080
that complimentary relationship where the founder 
and CEO know what they need and on the CPO side,  

863
01:12:36,080 --> 01:12:41,240
they know that they can mind meld enough 
with the CEO to actually have an impact.

864
01:12:41,240 --> 01:12:47,400
Last question. You started as an intern 
in the PR department, I think, at Meta?

865
01:12:47,400 --> 01:12:49,280
Oh, I started as a temp, actually.

