888
01:14:59,280 --> 01:15:04,120
to acquire power in the world. So it's interesting 
that now that seed has planted in my head. Anyway,  

889
01:15:04,120 --> 01:15:09,360
just A plug for that other episode also.
Ami, is there anything else that you wanted  

890
01:15:09,360 --> 01:15:13,200
to share or leave listeners with before 
we get to a very exciting lightning round?

891
01:15:13,200 --> 01:15:17,280
Sometimes people ask me who are working in 
product, what's the one thing they should do  

892
01:15:17,280 --> 01:15:25,320
to be successful at product? And maybe the thing 
I would say is, especially as an org scale or a  

893
01:15:25,320 --> 01:15:31,040
company scales, there's just a lot of distractions 
that get between you and the customer. And so the  

894
01:15:31,040 --> 01:15:36,600
one thing that I would just advise everyone 
to do is just think about the customer,  

895
01:15:36,600 --> 01:15:41,800
talk to the customer, be an advocate for them. 
It's such a shortcut to everything else you need  

896
01:15:41,800 --> 01:15:48,080
to do in order to be successful, but it's so easy 
for that to get lost when you're thinking about,  

897
01:15:48,080 --> 01:15:53,520
okay, how do I get alignment on my team? How 
do I figure out my roadmap? How do I convince  

898
01:15:53,520 --> 01:15:57,680
people to join the company? There's all these 
different things, but fundamentally, we're here  

899
01:15:57,680 --> 01:16:03,480
to create value for the customer. And the closer 
you can get to that, I always found myself the  

900
01:16:03,480 --> 01:16:08,260
happiest because I'm building that feedback loop 
with the customer, but also more successful.

901
01:16:08,260 --> 01:16:12,760
Well, let me actually follow up on this because 
this is really important and interesting. There's  

902
01:16:12,760 --> 01:16:16,800
a PM part of my brain of like, okay, but we 
also got to move some metrics and sometimes  

903
01:16:16,800 --> 01:16:21,320
that metric isn't going to be moved by, we need 
to do something specifically for the customer,  

904
01:16:21,320 --> 01:16:24,320
but it's something that will help the 
business. Is there anything there of  

905
01:16:24,320 --> 01:16:29,440
just that balance of like, we need 
to move over this conversion metric,  

906
01:16:29,440 --> 01:16:34,240
versus, let's focus fully on what does the 
customer want and need? Any thoughts there?

907
01:16:34,240 --> 01:16:40,520
Yeah, I think we often make things adversarial 
that are not actually adversarial. It is very  

908
01:16:40,520 --> 01:16:47,640
rare for customer value to be different than a 
company value on a long enough time horizon. There  

909
01:16:47,640 --> 01:16:53,320
might be short-term divergences, but really, 
to solve, to create value for the customer,  

910
01:16:53,320 --> 01:16:58,920
you got to be around as a business, otherwise 
you are creating zero value for the customer.  

911
01:16:58,920 --> 01:17:07,080
And so I think really, just starting with 
the, what are the end goals and where does  

912
01:17:07,080 --> 01:17:12,560
stuff diverge in the very short term versus the 
medium term versus in the long term? It shouldn't,  

913
01:17:12,560 --> 01:17:16,480
and really thinking about where you are in the 
journey and how to place that. That always helps  

914
01:17:16,480 --> 01:17:21,640
me because our metrics should absolutely 
be about long-term customer impact. It's  

915
01:17:21,640 --> 01:17:25,820
very rare if those aren't, and then 
you're still able to be successful.

916
01:17:25,820 --> 01:17:29,960
It comes back to our chat about 
metrics and how to do those well. 

917
01:17:29,960 --> 01:17:33,784
With that, we've reached our 
very exciting lightning round.

